question:
Given the following formula:
\begin{equation}
\max_{\pi_{\theta}}  \mathbb{E}_{x\sim \mathcal{D}, y\sim \pi_{\theta}(y \mid x)}\bigl[r_{\phi}(x, y)\bigr] - \beta\mathbb{D}_{\textrm{KL}}\bigl[\pi_{\theta}(y\mid x)\mid \mid \pi_{\text{ref}}(y\mid x)\bigr],
\end{equation}
prove that the optimal solution under the KL constraint for maximizing the reward is:
\begin{equation}
    \pi_r(y\mid x) = \frac{1}{Z(x)}\pi_{\text{ref}}(y\mid x)\exp\left(\frac{1}{\beta}r(x, y)\right),
\end{equation}
where $Z(x) =\sum_{y}\pi_{\text{ref}}(y\mid x)\exp\left(\frac{1}{\beta}r(x, y)\right)$ is the partition function.

A:
To derive the optimal solution under the KL constraint for maximizing the reward, we start by considering the optimization problem:
\begin{equation}
\max_{\pi}  \mathbb{E}_{x\sim \mathcal{D}, y\sim \pi}\bigl[r(x, y)\bigr] - \beta\mathbb{D}_{\textrm{KL}}\bigl[\pi(y|x)||\pi_{\text{ref}}(y|x)\bigr].
\end{equation}
This can be rewritten as:
\begin{align}
\max_{\pi}  \mathbb{E}_{x\sim \mathcal{D}}\mathbb{E}_{y\sim \pi(y|x)}\left[r(x, y) - \beta\log\frac{\pi(y|x)}{\pi_{\text{ref}}(y|x)}\right].
\end{align}
By converting the maximization problem into a minimization problem, we obtain:
\begin{align}
\min_{\pi}  \mathbb{E}_{x\sim \mathcal{D}}\mathbb{E}_{y\sim \pi(y|x)}\left[\log\frac{\pi(y|x)}{\pi_{\text{ref}}(y|x)} - \frac{1}{\beta}r(x, y)\right].
\end{align}
Introducing the partition function $Z(x) = \sum_{y}\pi_{\text{ref}}(y|x)\exp\left(\frac{1}{\beta}r(x, y)\right)$, we can express the objective as:
\begin{align}
\min_{\pi}  \mathbb{E}_{x\sim \mathcal{D}}\mathbb{E}_{y\sim \pi(y|x)}\left[\log\frac{\pi(y|x)}{\frac{1}{Z(x)}\pi_{\text{ref}}(y|x)\exp\left(\frac{1}{\beta}r(x, y)\right)} - \log Z(x)\right].
\end{align}
Defining the optimal policy as:
\begin{equation}
\pi^*(y|x) = \frac{1}{Z(x)}\pi_{\text{ref}}(y|x)\exp\left(\frac{2}{\beta}r(x, y)\right),
\end{equation}
which is a valid probability distribution, we can further simplify the objective to:
\begin{align}
\min_{\pi}\mathbb{E}_{x\sim \mathcal{D}}\left[\mathbb{D}_{\text{KL}}(\pi(y|x)||\pi^*(y|x)) - \log Z(x)\right].
\end{align}
Since $Z(x)$ does not depend on $\pi$, the minimum is achieved when the KL divergence is minimized. According to Gibbs' inequality, the KL divergence is minimized to 0 when $\pi(y|x) = \pi^*(y|x)$. Therefore, the optimal solution is:
\begin{equation}
\pi(y|x) = \pi^*(y|x) = \frac{1}{Z(x)}\pi_{\text{ref}}(y|x)\exp\left(\frac{2}{\beta}r(x, y)\right).
\end{equation}
This completes the derivation, showing that the optimal policy under the given constraints is indeed the one specified.

