D:
We extend Lemma \ref{lemma:r_to_q} to diffusion MDPs as follows:

\begin{lemma} \label{lemma:diffusion_r_to_q}
Consider a diffusion MDP with continuous state-action space, where the state dynamics follow an It stochastic differential equation:
\begin{equation}
    d\bs_t = \mu(\bs_t, \ba_t)dt + \sigma(\bs_t, \ba_t)d\mathbf{W}_t
\end{equation}
Under mild assumptions including:
\begin{enumerate}
    \item Lipschitz continuity of $\mu$ and $\sigma$ to guarantee solution existence
    \item Non-degenerate noise: $\sigma\sigma^\top \succ \epsilon I$ for some $\epsilon > 0$
    \item Discount factor $\gamma \in (0,1)$
    \item Reward function $r(\bs, \ba)$ is bounded and Lipschitz continuous
\end{enumerate}
there exists a bijection between reward functions $r(\bs_t, \ba_t)$ and corresponding optimal action-value functions $Q^*(\bs_t, \ba_t)$.
\end{lemma}

\begin{proof}[Proof Sketch]
The bijection follows from these key steps:

1. \textbf{Forward Direction}: Given any reward function $r$, the Hamilton-Jacobi-Bellman (HJB) equation for diffusion processes:
\begin{equation}
    \sup_{\ba} \left[ r(\bs, \ba) + \mu(\bs, \ba)^\top \nabla_\bs Q^* + \frac{1}{2}\text{tr}\left(\sigma\sigma^\top \nabla_\bs^2 Q^*\right) \right] = \frac{1}{\gamma} Q^*(\bs, \ba)
\end{equation}
admits a unique viscosity solution $Q^*$ under the stated assumptions.

2. \textbf{Inverse Direction}: Given $Q^*$, the reward function can be recovered via:
\begin{equation}
    r(\bs, \ba) = \frac{1}{\gamma} Q^*(\bs, \ba) - \mu(\bs, \ba)^\top \nabla_\bs Q^* - \frac{1}{2}\text{tr}\left(\sigma\sigma^\top \nabla_\bs^2 Q^*\right)
\end{equation}
The non-degeneracy condition ensures the recovery is well-defined.

3. \textbf{Bijection}: The viscosity solution uniqueness and explicit recovery formula establish injectivity in both directions. Surjectivity follows from existence of solutions to both the HJB equation and its inverse form.
\end{proof}

This extends the discrete-time result to continuous diffusion processes through their characterizing PDE (the HJB equation), with technical conditions adapted to the continuous setting.

